('49336', '7027780465', 1, 'f', NULL, 0, 0, 0, '2023-03-18', 'Alkyl glucosides used and still technically are considered mild and gentle BUT several years ago were found to actually be allergens that can cause allergic dermatitis reactions. Literally won allergen of the year in 2017. You can google the studies. While a lot of people won‚Äôt have reactions many don‚Äôt realise that the reason they are breaking out in bumps, redness, little white heads all over is from a reaction to glucosides in products. They are in so many amazing products from all brands and all types of products because it‚Äôs still considered gen√©rele and mild but just know that if you are prone to contact dermatitis, have a compromised skin barrier, or sensitive skin in general you should try your best to shy away from glucosides. The most commonly used being decyl glucoside. If you‚Äôre one of many that have used Glow recipe and loved the result but not the reaction of breakout you got. Check the list. It‚Äôs in the eye cream etc. you might have less of a reaction with rinse offs such as cleansers BUT studies show that you should refrain from even using rinse offs because of worsening future reactions. Hoping this helps people who have had issues with skincare and can‚Äôt seem to figure out what the ingredient is. Glucosides come up in search as being safe for sensitive skin until you keep researching. A lot of sunscreens use it as well and it‚Äôs not always the uva/uvb ingredient irritating your skin.', 'Warning for contact dermatitis and sensitive skin!', NULL, 'brown', 'combination', NULL, 'P505274', 'Glucoside Foaming Cleanser', 'The Ordinary', 12.5),
